Manuscript.Body:
When we arrive, the spaces between the buildings are strangely vacant. The escaped horses are hitched back to the familiar carriage, parked at the side of the headquarters: surely the royals are elsewhere, enjoying the finest accommodations.  I can hear a loud group of guards and civilians within the walls. I lament the straight walk through the center of the building we&apos;ll have to take to get Bertram the attention he needs.
I can hear the voices of the commoners.
&quot;If your guards were smart enough to know how to walk and run, we wouldn&apos;t be in this mess.&quot;
&quot;You need to get rid of her. They need a gesture of our apology. Send her to the front lines immediately!&quot;
&quot;Oh, give her a break! Clumsy or not, she&apos;s the reason the patriarch is still alive.&quot;
All the heads turn when we enter. I&apos;m the first to step in, and all the eyes fall on me.
&quot;About time you come back after scampering off,&quot; a senior guard says.
&quot;I wasn&apos;t &apos;scampering off,&apos;&quot; I tell him. &quot;I was saving the other victim everyone forgot about.&quot;
Pax enters next, carrying the real Bertram in his arms now. He steps carefully between villagers seated on the floor.
&quot;Gods above,&quot; another says.
I find Aldrin standing at the front of the room: his natural height is enough to demand attention. &quot;This only proves further that today was far from a failure. I know you are all scared of repercussions, of tribute lost, but it doesn&apos;t change the fact that Gaffesend is vital to the defense of our homeland.&quot;
Since I&apos;m able to catch my breath for the first time, I walk around the back of the room to stand beside Jullian, but he doesn&apos;t turn to me, focused on the words of our leader.
&quot;I know it wasn&apos;t perfect. They&apos;re still learning, but they took action, and I want to recognize the bravery of Pax and Katiya, and their quick reactions to the evil vice of our enemy.&quot;
He raises his hands to try and start a cheer, but the room is quiet.
&quot;We don&apos;t care about bravery, we care about safety. How can we be sure our village is really safe?&quot; Someone says. The other villagers agree.
&quot;This was an act to incite fear, to make it feel like a losing battle,&quot; Aldrin says. &quot;It was an act of attacking the mind of a people, not an act of definite power!&quot;
&quot;But what if it was?&quot; One of the farmers says. &quot;I stare into the darkness every night in the southeast, how can I be sure of that?&quot;
&quot;We need more than just the professional guards, more than the army, we need everything you have!&quot;
&quot;Then we will do something about it.&quot;
&quot;Do what? The empire will support us less after this!&quot;
&quot;We&apos;ll send out the junior guards,&quot; Aldrin says.
I can feel the freedom to choose, to be decidedly safe, dissolving away. The numbness returns to my fingers.
&quot;Night missions. Indefinite night scouting missions, and during the day, too,&quot; Aldrin offers, the first thing that seems to quell the fears across the town hall. &quot;No more idle quests, we&apos;ll place them at the threshold.&quot;
The cheer grows louder. My heart beats faster.
&quot;We will do everything in our power to keep this town safe. And we&apos;ll re-institute the volunteer force if needed. I promise you,&quot; he says, and when I reach for a space behind Jullian to sit, the others stand.
Before long, the townies are leaving, satisfied enough with the answer. I reach for Jullian&apos;s hand, but he&apos;s gone without a word, and I feel like I deserve it.
I can feel the static on my flesh. When I&apos;m far enough behind my friends, I stumble home, feeling the weakness begin to overtake me. My curling fingers fumble for the key. My name will be scratched off it soon. I&apos;m too humiliated to ask for Jullian&apos;s comfort when he never stays in the first place, my other friend is fighting for his life, and it feels like the only option I have is to invoke the help of the stranger I shut out so many weeks ago.
I press desperately against the shelf as my body curls on itself, praying that the passageway is still there and I won&apos;t crumple in the closet. I crack the door, struggling to drive it against the bookshelf since I didn&apos;t push it far enough, trying to slide my body only to find a second door firmly locked in place.
I remember the strange name of the foreign language I can somehow understand, and I cry it like an incantation. 
&quot;Cody. Help me, please,&quot; I beg, pounding on the door. &quot;Cody!&quot;
The door latches. I hear a shrill, ear-piercing screech sound from beneath my foot as something finesses heavy piece of metal bracing the door. His hand rips the screeching thing to pieces before he manages to leverage it open, killing the metallic creature mid-cry.
When the door opens, all I can manage is to collapse into his arms, and he embraces me, leading me into his foyer as the tears run from my eyes.
His voice is soothing as he tries to calm me. It&apos;s the only sense I have when my eyes are shut, trying to abate the fear of all the artifacts around me. I can feel my back settle into the comfortable couch where I found his friend sleeping, and he sits beside me, placing his arm around me at enough of a distance to prevent me from thinking that he&apos;s trying to make a move.
&quot;So, uh, what happened?&quot;

About a month passes since the self-defense festival. After a memorable day of ale and laughter where the knights and their civilian counterparts celebrate late into the night, the spirit of the town of Gaffesend settles back into the air of nervous unease. The sounds of cheer no longer make the noise of the distant war machine, wondering every moonless night whether it&apos;s getting closer or further, and though my stomach rises again with the terror of the unknown, I find a strange respite when I remember Cody&apos;s warless world is right next door.
But I hate it.
So often my mind races through scenarios &mdash; whether it&apos;s a fire, a siege, or a shelling of amethyst mortars &mdash; wondering how I&apos;ll react when it happens, if I might flee to that pacifistic realm of peace, and what it would take to withstand a moment of weakness like that.
But it&apos;s so enthralling that it captures my mind, when I&apos;m away on my quests in the town. It&apos;s been weeks since I chased the half-blood Ahkva: the few guards that witnessed the leap have already forgotten my act of courage, and all that remains is the memory of my failure to defend the nobles.
But today is different. Though Cody and I no longer lock our doors, saying hello when we return from long days working in our worlds, he&apos;s invited me to an event at his place of employment, and at week&apos;s end, I have the entire day off.
He peeks through the doorway, gesturing to the outfit I assembled on minimum knowledge. &quot;What the hell is that?&quot;
&quot;You said pants. And I&apos;m wearing the shirt you gave me,&quot; I say. He glares at me. &quot;What? All I have from your world is this shirt.&quot;
&quot;A surf shirt . . . that you&apos;re going to wear to a formal event?&quot; He asks. &quot;I knew you grew up in the sticks, but don&apos;t you have anything that&apos;s at least a little nice?&quot;
&quot;It&apos;s not my fault I wear the armor to everything: I could only bring a hundred pounds of possessions with me. The military curated my whole closet!&quot;
&quot;Then&mdash;&quot; Cody checks his watch. He sighs. &quot;I&apos;ve got something else for you, then.&quot;
Cody races up the stairs. As I step into his realm, I hear the clatter of hangers in his closet as he looks for the perfect shirt.
He returns with a finely-woven collared shirt embellished with the letters NAVIDSON-MONROE ENGINEERING DEPT. over the heart. &quot;I won this in a raffle for New Years last year. All the shirts were just leftovers from the storeroom, and this was a medium.&quot; He hands it to me. &quot;Can you imagine that? Billion dollar company that makes its employees pay for logoed shirts. And yours are all free.&quot;
I take it from him. &quot;I pay my giving my damn life, and letting them own me for years,&quot; I say.
&quot;Oh,&quot; he says. &quot;That&apos;s a good point, I guess.&quot;
I use Cody&apos;s restroom to change into the shirt. I can hear his nervous impatience as he taps his nails against the kitchen counter, and when I look in the mirror, I can&apos;t even recognize myself, looking so much like a civilian from his world.
He judges me when I open the door. His face twists into a light sneer.
&quot;What? I look just like one of your people.&quot;
&quot;I mean, besides the eyes&mdash;&quot;
&quot;You can&apos;t change my eyes,&quot; I say.
&quot;I know,&quot; he says. &quot;But the pants. Don&apos;t you just have, like, a pair of jeans or something?&quot;
&quot;Jeans? This is all I have,&quot; I say.
&quot;Okay,&quot; he says. He opens his mouth as if he wants to continue, but he stops.
&quot;No, what?&quot; I ask.
&quot;Uh , nothing,&quot; he says.
&quot;No, what were you going to say?&quot;
&quot;I was just thinking . . . I should take you shopping, you know. If you&apos;re going to be spending more time in my world.&quot;
&quot;But I don&apos;t have any dollars,&quot; I say.
&quot;It&apos;s okay. I do,&quot; he says.
&quot;But what about your debt?&quot;
&quot;The mortgage? I&apos;m doing fine. As long as I don&apos;t get fired,&quot; he says. &quot;How about you take me shopping in your world?&quot;



He peeks into my home to find I&apos;m wearing the only clothes I&apos;ve been given from his world. It&apos;s just the surf shirt: washed, of course, along with the finely-woven pants of my knight&apos;s uniform, traced down the front of the knee in a line of gold, with more pockets than any other piece of clothing I have.

I grit my teeth and continue to descend into the cold tub. My body aches, but not yet from the freezing water. It&apos;s from the pain of how heavy-handed those backwater Ahkvasans are &mdash; digging their manicured claws into the thinnest muscles on our backs, extracting pain from our overworked muscles by dealing it. And now I&apos;m tasked to withstand the freezing water for a couple minutes, because it&apos;s supposedly good for me.
&quot;No Essence,&quot; Jullian says, seemingly humored by my suffering as he recovers in the warm tub. &quot;I didn&apos;t do it with Essence. No cheating!&quot;
&quot;What, you think I&apos;m a cheater?&quot; I ask. The ache seeps into my bones, as if my marrow is infected with the Chymaeran Curse. 
My face twitches. 
I ask, &quot;and how long did you say this was for?&quot;
&quot;Five minutes,&quot; he says.
I tremble as gooseflesh spreads like a rash, feeling parts of my body contract that are beyond my control. &quot;Well, talk to me about something. I talked to you, didn&apos;t I?&quot;
&quot;Aren&apos;t we kind of out of things to talk about?&quot; He says.
&quot;How about the,&quot; my teeth chatter, &quot;how about how pointless this place is for people like us?&quot;
He laughs. &quot;Just because you hate the cold tub&mdash;&quot;
&quot;No. Not the Gods-damn cold tub. I mean &mdash; can&apos;t anything be made a warm tub with our abilities? We could get in the bath at home and heat it in moments.&quot;
&quot;But what about the nature?&quot; Jullian says, spreading his arms as he gestures to the open-air naked bath. &quot;What about the trip? Getting a little ways out of Gaffesend? The water has special properties. They say it heals you.&quot;
&quot;We can heal ourselves, too, you know.&quot; I tense my jaw shut to stop that Gods-awful sound of bone-on-bone.
He smirks. &quot;Sounds like you don&apos;t like this date.&quot;
&quot;I do. All that doesn&apos;t mean this isn&apos;t nice. It&apos;s pain, just like every day. But it&apos;s good pain. Pain that&apos;s for you, you know?&quot;
&quot;For you?&quot; He asks. &quot;Isn&apos;t all pain for the person in pain?&quot;
&quot;No, but pain that makes you better. Half the pain of our training is just lifting stuff all day, or walking laps around the border. But this is to make you feel better later.&quot; My arms tighten around each other as I shiver. &quot;Or it&apos;s supposed to. Right?&quot;
&quot;Sounds to me like your brain is starting to freeze,&quot; he says. &quot;Maybe you should get out. And admit you&apos;re weaker than me.&quot;
&quot;Or maybe you should admit you&apos;re bad at distracting me! Make me feel better,&quot; I say. &quot;Relax me.&quot;
&quot;I&apos;m not getting in there with you,&quot; he says.
&quot;Then talk about . . . the future,&quot; I say.
&quot;What about it?&quot;
&quot;About us. About what happens after all of this. After the trials, after probation and all.&quot;
I expect his face to warm a little. Maybe from the thought of us living together and depending on each other like we planned, and I want to warm my spirit on that when my body freezes. But he hardly seems to give it a thought.
&quot;I don&apos;t know, haven&apos;t really thought about it,&quot; he says. &quot;I&apos;m more focused on what&apos;s happening right now.&quot;
&quot;But really, though,&quot; I say. &quot;You haven&apos;t thought about any of it?&quot;
&quot;I think I&apos;m already in the future I wanted,&quot; I say. &quot;And I hope tomorrow is just a continuation of that. Just the prospect of being free is enough: from all those awful years I never had the freedom to do anything. School, then training, then taking care of my brothers. Sleep for a while. Then repeat it all over again,&quot; he says.
&quot;You met me in those years,&quot; I say, losing the feeling of ice.
&quot;Oh. I mean, of course,&quot; he says. &quot;And you saved me from doing that forever. Could you imagine our lives if we weren&apos;t free like this? Boyhood was something I never had. And surely you&apos;d admit that you didn&apos;t have a childhood either.&quot;
&quot;I had a piece of one,&quot; I say. &quot;But what we have now is control. To steer our lives somewhere better. That after all the hard work and delayed gratification, we can reach something and call it ours. That thing we both wanted, remember?&quot;
&quot;I remember.&quot; 
He opens his mouth to modify that statement, but he pauses.
&quot;But what?&quot; I ask.
&quot;I remember being the oldest after both my brothers were born. I remember the school day as the only time I had to enjoy myself. And my friends: Gavin and Auren, and how they&apos;d keep inviting me to things, again and again, turning them down every time since I had to walk home and pick up my stupid siblings and feed them. While they got girlfriends, and they forgot about me, and got new friends, and . . .&quot; Jullian clenches his fist and drives it into her water, but it doesn&apos;t launch a plume of hot water. His fist sizzles, sending clouds of water vapor to join the miasmic haze that hovers over the pools. &quot;You remember the Harvest Festival before we left, I&apos;m sure.&quot;
&quot;Of course. The last real fun we had back there,&quot; I say. &quot;Just the two of us, walking between booths.&quot;
&quot;That was the first festival I&apos;ve ever been to. And it just . . . gave me a taste of something. Like trying ice cream for the first time at age twenty.&quot; I feel like he wants me to extrapolate the meaning, but I don&apos;t get it. Like &mdash; is it so wrong?&quot;
&quot;Is what so wrong?&quot; I ask.
&quot;So wrong to wish for something.&quot;
&quot;To wish for what?&quot;
&quot;To wish my father never died in the mining accident: to knock up my mother and leave me to care for them. Or to wish they were never born, and I could have enjoyed my life. Or if I can&apos;t go back there, then to&mdash;&quot; 
But then he stops himself in his moment of passion. He recoils, frightened of his true nature for just a moment until his expression glazes over.
&quot;Nevermind,&quot; he says.
&quot;No. Finish the thought,&quot; I say, losing sense of the freezing water. &quot;What is it you wish for?&quot;
&quot;For nothing,&quot; he insists. I can feel the anger and disappointment of all these months flood through me, but it can&apos;t come out of my mouth. I&apos;m choking on it, like holding back the urge to vomit: the thought of the something that comes after those words. It&apos;s the thought of oblivion. That with how things are going at training, that I&apos;m headed for death anyways. That I don&apos;t have the time or the temerity or the looks or the emotional energy, and with all that fear, all I can do is keep holding it here.
I bite my tongue until I think it bleeds, shutting my eyes as I fail to recognize what it does to me. He rattles off with some reason he&apos;s found the time to invent, and as the panic makes me sweat like those sleepless nights in the dream, I can feel the fingers closing in on me, surrounding my body with scentless smoke.
And then I breathe. I think of things that rest me, but nothing works. The morning runs. The view from my house in the evenings. The love we had. And only when his face crosses my mind &mdash; that smug face when he insults me, but in a friendly way; the expression he wears when he&apos;s deep in focus; the way his forearms fill the space when he rolls his sleeves &mdash; the thought of Cody gives me a sense of control, of resistance. 
And so I open my eyes to find the water no longer at my shoulders. It boils beneath my bottom as I sit here in a ball, wondering how much longer I have to savor this mediocrity before I&apos;m sent off to die.
I rise from the tub, covering my breasts with my arms as Jullian&apos;s eyes snare on something in the distance, too much of a coward to turn and face me, or even himself. 
But maybe that similarity makes us perfect for each other.
&quot;I wish I could be enough to you,&quot;I say, managing just a single sentence before the tears start to flow. I rush to the changing room as Jullian just sits there, without the strength to call after me or even follow.
